Most “AI in the browser” articles show you a demo. This one shows you what actually breaks when you ship it to production.
We run a machine learning model — a 44MB neural network that performs semantic image segmentation — entirely inside the user’s browser. No server-side inference. No API calls. No file uploads. The model downloads once, caches locally, and runs on the user’s CPU.
This isn’t a demo. It’s a production tool used by real people to remove backgrounds from photos.
This article is about everything that went wrong.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Why Browser-Based AI Matters
The standard approach to AI-powered web tools is simple: user uploads a file → server runs inference → server returns the result. remove.bg, Photoroom, and most “AI” online tools work this way. It works, but it has three structural problems:
Privacy. When you upload a photo to a background remover, that photo sits on someone else’s server. You don’t know how long it’s stored, who can access it, or whether it’s used to train future models. For product photos, NDA documents, or personal images, this is a dealbreaker.
Cost. Server-side inference costs money per request. GPU instances are expensive. Every free-tier AI tool is either running at a loss, harvesting data to compensate, or will eventually add limits. The economics only work if users pay — which is why most “free” AI tools have aggressive upsell funnels.
Latency. Upload time + queue time + inference time + download time. For a single image, that’s 5–15 seconds of network overhead before the AI even starts working.
Browser-based AI solves all three: the file never leaves the device, inference is free (it runs on the user’s CPU), and there’s no network round-trip. The tradeoff is that you’re now responsible for making a neural network run inside a browser tab without crashing. That’s where the fun begins.
The Stack: What’s Actually Running
Before we get to the problems, here’s what’s actually happening when someone uses our background remover:

• RMBG-1.4 — a 44MB ONNX model from Hugging Face that performs foreground segmentation. It identifies the subject of an image (person, product, animal) and generates a pixel-level alpha mask.

• Transformers.js — a JavaScript library by Hugging Face that runs ONNX models in the browser. Under the hood, it uses ONNX Runtime Web, which compiles the model’s operations to WebAssembly.

• Web Workers — the model runs in a background thread, separate from the main UI thread. Without this, the browser would freeze during inference.

• Cache API — the 44MB model file is cached after first download, so subsequent visits load instantly.
The user experience: drag a photo onto the page → model loads (first time only, ~10 seconds on broadband) → background removed in 2–5 seconds → download transparent PNG. The file never touches a server.
Now let’s talk about what breaks.
Challenge 1: Loading 44MB Without Freezing the Browser
The model file is 44MB. If you download it synchronously on the main thread, the browser freezes. If you download it on page load without telling the user, they think the page is broken.
Solution: Load the model inside a Web Worker with explicit progress reporting.
// Main thread
const worker = new Worker('ai-worker.js');
​
worker.postMessage({ type: 'load-model' });
​
worker.onmessage = (e) => {
if (e.data.type === 'progress') {
updateProgressBar(e.data.loaded, e.data.total);
} else if (e.data.type === 'ready') {
enableFileInput();
}
};// ai-worker.js
import { pipeline } from '@huggingface/transformers';
​
self.pipeline = null;
​
self.onmessage = async (e) => {
if (e.data.type === 'load-model') {
// Fetch the model with progress tracking
const response = await fetch(modelUrl);
const reader = response.body.getReader();
const contentLength = +response.headers.get('Content-Length');
let receivedLength = 0;
​
// Stream to cache while reporting progress
const cache = await caches.open('ai-models');
const chunks = [];
while (true) {
const { done, value } = await reader.read();
if (done) break;
chunks.push(value);
receivedLength += value.length;
self.postMessage({
type: 'progress',
loaded: receivedLength,
total: contentLength
});
} // Cache the model for future visits
const blob = new Blob(chunks);
await cache.put(modelUrl, new Response(blob));
// Load the model from cache
self.pipeline = await pipeline('background-removal', 'briaai/RMBG-1.4', {
device: 'wasm',
});
self.postMessage({ type: 'ready' });
}
};
The key insight: show progress, disable interaction until ready, and cache aggressively. A 44MB download with no progress bar looks like a broken page. A 44MB download with a progress bar looks like software loading.
Cache strategy: We use the Cache API (not localStorage — it’s too small, and not IndexedDB — it’s unnecessarily complex for a single file). After the first load, caches.match() returns the model instantly. The browser cache survives across sessions, so returning users get the tool immediately.
Model updates and cache invalidation: The model URL includes a version segment — /models/rmbg-1.4/v1/onnx/model.onnx. When we ship a new model version, we bump the URL to /v2/. The Cache API keys by URL, so the new version is fetched fresh while the old cached version simply goes unused. No invalidation needed — old caches are eventually evicted by the browser's LRU policy. We also clean up stale versions on load:
const MODEL_VERSION = 'v1';
const MODEL_URL = `/models/rmbg-1.4/${MODEL_VERSION}/onnx/model.onnx`;
​
// Clean up old model versions from cache
async function pruneOldModelCache() {
const cache = await caches.open('ai-models');
const keys = await cache.keys();
for (const request of keys) {
// Keep only the current version
if (!request.url.includes(`/rmbg-1.4/${MODEL_VERSION}/`)) {
await cache.delete(request);
}
}
}This matters because 44MB per version adds up. A user who visited during v1 and again during v2 would otherwise accumulate 88MB of cached model files with no way to know the old one is stale.
Challenge 2: Memory Math — The Invisible Ceiling
Here’s the part nobody talks about. Running an ML model in the browser isn’t just about downloading 44MB. It’s about the total memory footprint during inference.
Let’s do the math for a 1920×1080 image:
Press enter or click to view image in full size

ComponentMemoryModel file (loaded into WASM memory)~44MBInput image (decoded to raw RGB pixels)~6MB (1920×1080×3)Intermediate tensors (model internal state)~50–100MB depending on architectureOutput mask (full-resolution alpha channel)~2MB (1920×1080×1)Original image (kept for compositing)~6MBTotal peak memory~110–160MB
That doesn’t sound like much. But here’s the catch: browser tabs have memory ceilings.
On desktop Chrome, a single tab can typically use 2–4GB before the browser’s OOM (Out of Memory) killer steps in. That’s plenty for a single image.
On mobile Safari (iOS), the limit is much tighter — around 200–300MB for a single tab on devices with 2–3GB RAM. Our model’s peak memory usage of 110–160MB is dangerously close to that ceiling. Add the browser’s own overhead (page DOM, JavaScript engine, rendering), and you’re one large image away from a crash.
Solution: resize before inference.
// Before running inference, downscale large images
const MAX_DIMENSION = 1024;
let { width, height } = imageBitmap;
​
if (width > MAX_DIMENSION || height > MAX_DIMENSION) {
const scale = MAX_DIMENSION / Math.max(width, height);
width = Math.round(width * scale);
height = Math.round(height * scale); // Resize using Canvas (GPU-accelerated)
const canvas = new OffscreenCanvas(width, height);
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
ctx.drawImage(imageBitmap, 0, 0, width, height);
imageBitmap = canvas.transferToImageBitmap();
}
We cap input at 1024px on the longest side before feeding it to the model. The segmentation quality is virtually identical — the model’s effective resolution is lower than 1024px anyway. But memory usage drops by 75% for a 4K input image.
The mask is then upscaled back to the original resolution using bilinear interpolation during compositing. Edge quality suffers slightly on very fine details (hair strands), but the tradeoff is: slightly softer edges vs. browser crash. It’s not a hard choice.
This isn’t just optimization. It’s a security boundary.
Here’s what most browser-based tool developers miss: the 1024px cap isn’t only about memory — it’s about preventing a deliberate browser DoS. A crafted PNG file can be a few megabytes compressed but decompress to a 50,000×50,000 pixel bitmap — that’s ~7GB of raw RGB data. The browser will dutifully try to decode it, allocate the memory, and crash the tab. Or worse, freeze the entire browser.
You need two hard limits:
// Hard limit 1: file size (before decoding)
const MAX_FILE_SIZE = 25 * 1024 * 1024; // 25MB
if (file.size > MAX_FILE_SIZE) {
throw new Error('File too large. Maximum 25MB.');
}
​
// Hard limit 2: decoded pixel dimensions (after decoding)
const MAX_PIXELS = 1024 * 1024; // 1MP — matches our inference cap
const imageBitmap = await createImageBitmap(file);
if (imageBitmap.width * imageBitmap.height > MAX_PIXELS * 4) {
// Allow up to 4MP input (we'll downscale before inference),
// but reject anything absurd
imageBitmap.close();
throw new Error('Image dimensions too large. Maximum 4096×4096.');
}File size is checked first because it’s free — you know file.size before decoding anything. The pixel check happens after createImageBitmap, which means the browser has already decoded the image, but at least you catch it before feeding it to the model. The gap between these two checks (a small file that decodes to huge dimensions) is the attack surface. You can't fully close it — browsers don't let you inspect image dimensions without decoding — but the file size limit narrows it significantly.
Without these limits, you’re one malicious upload away from a frozen tab. With them, you’ve turned a crash into a friendly error message.
Challenge 3: Safari’s WASM Memory Limit
WebAssembly has a hard memory limit in Safari: 4GB per module. This sounds generous, but ONNX Runtime Web internally allocates memory for model weights, intermediate tensors, and execution buffers. A 44MB model can balloon to 200–400MB of WASM memory after decompression and tensor allocation.
For most images, this is fine. But we’ve seen Safari tab crashes on:

• Very large images (4000×3000+ from DSLR cameras)

• Batch processing (multiple images in sequence without releasing memory)

• Devices with less than 4GB total RAM (older iPhones, iPad mini)
Solution: explicit memory management and graceful failure.
async function removeBackground(imageFile) {
let imageBitmap = null;
let result = null;
​
try {
imageBitmap = await createImageBitmap(file);
​
// Safari: use a tighter cap
const isSafari = /^((?!chrome|android).)*safari/i.test(navigator.userAgent);
const maxDim = isSafari ? 768 : 1024;
​
// Resize before inference (see Challenge 2)
imageBitmap = await resizeIfNeeded(imageBitmap, maxDim);
​
result = await pipeline(imageBitmap);
return result;
} catch (error) {
if (error.message.includes('memory') || error.name === 'RangeError') {
throw new Error(
'This image is too large for browser processing. ' +
'Try a smaller image (under 2000×2000) or use a desktop browser.'
);
}
throw error;
} finally {
// Release what we can. JS has no manual GC,
// but nulling references lets the engine collect sooner.
if (imageBitmap) imageBitmap.close(); // Free decoded image memory
imageBitmap = null;
}
}Batch processing: the memory leak you don’t see. If you process multiple images in sequence — say, a user drops 20 product photos — the above pattern isn’t enough. Each iteration creates new ImageBitmap objects and intermediate tensors. If you don't explicitly release them between iterations, they pile up in memory until the tab crashes.
